<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-069-840  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 069 840.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Feb 20 1989 v6 n7 p60(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Electronic patient charts. (Medicomp microcomputer-based medicaldiagnosis and records-keeping information system) (BusinessApplications Digest: Healthcare)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Steinberg, Don.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Medicomp of Virginia Inc. (products).andO;Product:   Medicomp (computer program).andO;Topic:     Expert SystemsRecords ManagementMedical Advice SystemsNew ProductMicrocomputersHospital Information Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>You might look elsewhere than rural Minden, La., to find a recentlyintroduced, state-of-the-art, $28,000 medical expert system.andP;  However, Dr.andO;David Shepard, an internist 30 miles east of Shreveport, is the only doctorin the country who has it.andM;What he has is the PC version of the Medicomp system, from Medicomp ofFairfax, Va.andP;  Medicomp is an innovative patient-care system for doctors andhospitals that combines expert-system diagnosis of ailments with anear-comphrensive patient-recordkeeping system.andP;  Medicomp recently releasedit commercially after a decade of development.andM;The Medicomp system, which runs on a stand-alone Compaq Deskpro 386 with 300Mbytes of storage, maintains a paperless ''electronic chart'' on each patient.andO;Data on patient background, illnesses, medications, lab tests and physicalexams are entered into the system using laser-printed scan sheets, which arefilled out with No.andP;  2 pencils like standardized scholastic tests.andM;The paper scanning lets data-entry occur even where no computer exists.andP;  Labscan fill out scan sheets and mail them to Dr. Shepard's office, where theyare scanned and thus become part of electronic records.andM;Patients might even pencil in personal history sheets, essentially performingtheir own data entry, ''assuming the patient is conscious and so forth,''said Peter Goltra, Medicomp president.andM;The system also includes a 60M-byte, 26,000-symptom, 1,800-disease expertsystem through which patient data can be run.andM;The expert system gives Dr.andP;  Shepard second opinions on diagnoses andgenerates ''intelligent scan sheets'' that contain questions and tests morespecific to individual patients' conditions.andM;Dr.andP;  Shepard said the system has increased his income about $2,000 a month byletting him handle more patients.andP;  In addition, it has helped him raise thequality of his care, he said.andP;  Of course, that's not to mention the fact thatthe system's a lot of fun to play with.andM;''I could be driving a Porsche, but I have more fun with my computer.'' hesaid.andO;</TEXT></DOC>